The horse was not wild or untamable; it was afraid of its own shadow.

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:14.229
Alexander approached the horse, whispered into its ears to calm it

00:07:14.239 --> 00:07:19.229
down, and turned it towards the sun, so that it couldn’t see its shadow.

00:07:20.319 --> 00:07:25.449
He then jumped onto the back of the horse and rode away to rounds of applause.

00:07:26.409 --> 00:07:32.059
Now, this tale might be apocryphal, made up or exaggerated for

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:36.909
effect, but it gives you an idea of the legend of Alexander The Great.

00:07:37.989 --> 00:07:45.949
So, we are in 336 BC, King Phillip has just been assassinated, and his eldest son, the

00:07:45.999 --> 00:07:51.979
20-year-old Alexander has just taken over as the King of Macedon, or King of Macedonia.

00:07:53.219 --> 00:07:59.389
After eliminating potential rivals to his power, Alexander wasted no time in taking up

00:07:59.629 --> 00:08:05.029
where his father had left off, in terms of preparing to head east and invade Persia.

00:08:05.729 --> 00:08:08.939
Now, why Persia, you might be asking yourself?

00:08:09.799 --> 00:08:13.359
The Persians had invaded Greece a hundred years before,

00:08:13.689 --> 00:08:17.929
and there was a desire to get even, to avenge this attack.

00:08:19.089 --> 00:08:23.649
There was also the simple fact that the Persian empire was the richest in the

00:08:23.649 --> 00:08:29.389
world, and even though Greece was not exactly cash-strapped, literally all

00:08:29.409 --> 00:08:34.319
the riches of Persia awaited anyone who was able to topple the Persian ruler.

00:08:35.669 --> 00:08:40.619
And then there is the factor that is perhaps harder to verify, that

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:45.659
Alexander had some deep-rooted desire for personal glory and conquest.

00:08:46.579 --> 00:08:51.979
Clearly, there was some element of this, otherwise he wouldn’t have gone on a more than

00:08:51.989 --> 00:08:58.489
decade-long military campaign, but historians are divided over the extent to which this was some

00:08:58.529 --> 00:09:05.519
grand masterplan from the outset or whether it was more a case of “I’ve started, so I’ll go on”.

00:09:06.739 --> 00:09:12.539
In any case, he started, and he did go on, for 13 years, to be precise.

00:09:14.069 --> 00:09:21.489
The Persian ruler at this time was Darius III, an impressive ruler who commanded a huge army.

00:09:22.771 --> 00:09:28.691
The two armies first met at the Battle of Issus, in November of 333 BC.

00:09:29.351 --> 00:09:32.671
The Persian forces greatly outnumbered The Macedonians.

00:09:33.721 --> 00:09:40.401
Some ancient sources have the Persian army numbering as many as 600,000 to Alexander’s

00:09:40.591 --> 00:09:47.461
just under 40,000, although most modern estimates have the Persian forces at 60,000 or so.

00:09:48.461 --> 00:09:54.071
In any case, the odds were not in Alexander’s favour from a headcount perspective.

00:09:54.951 --> 00:09:58.431
But Alexander had several other advantages.

00:09:59.451 --> 00:10:03.471
Firstly, he had inherited his father’s excellently trained army.

00:10:04.001 --> 00:10:10.491
The Macedonians were fierce warriors, skilled and practised in the business of warfare.

00:10:11.521 --> 00:10:15.921
They also had highly sophisticated weapons: the army included foot

00:10:15.931 --> 00:10:21.741
soldiers with huge spears 6 metres long, who formed large impenetrable

00:10:21.741 --> 00:10:25.491
squares, because of these long sharp spears that pointed out.

00:10:26.281 --> 00:10:33.371
If you imagine a sort of square porcupine with deadly sharp metal spikes, that gives you some idea.

00:10:34.621 --> 00:10:39.951
There were also heavily armoured cavalry, soldiers on horses, who could charge at an enemy and

00:10:39.951 --> 00:10:46.471
inflict serious damage, as well as skilled archers, people firing arrows high into the sky.

00:10:47.911 --> 00:10:54.041
Alexander had been given leadership roles in battles while his father was still alive, so he

00:10:54.041 --> 00:10:58.971
had learned the most effective strategies and techniques of using these different types of

00:10:58.971 --> 00:11:04.581
soldiers and weapons against his enemies, and how to best position them on the battlefield.

00:11:06.121 --> 00:11:12.921
What’s more his soldiers were incredibly well drilled and disciplined, they were professionals.

00:11:14.261 --> 00:11:17.891
And Alexander knew the importance of keeping morale high,

00:11:18.121 --> 00:11:22.081
of making his soldiers believe in him and in themselves.

00:11:23.291 --> 00:11:29.131
He did this through rousing speeches, but perhaps the most obvious and important

00:11:29.141 --> 00:11:34.111
way in which he achieved this was through fighting on the frontlines himself.

00:11:35.121 --> 00:11:39.621
He was not the sort of person to stand on his horse on a high piece of ground far

00:11:39.621 --> 00:11:45.341
away from the action; he was there fighting side by side with his men, slaying

00:11:45.381 --> 00:11:50.881
Persians left right and centre and coming inches from death on multiple occasions.

00:11:52.461 --> 00:11:58.131
And at Issus, the first major battle against the full might of the Persian

00:11:58.131 --> 00:12:03.501
army, this all came together and the Macedonians emerged victorious.

00:12:04.895 --> 00:12:10.422
Darius was not killed nor was his army crushed, but enough of a defeat was

00:12:10.432 --> 00:12:15.532
inflicted that he tried to strike a bargain with Alexander, a peace deal.

00:12:16.592 --> 00:12:22.112
He would give Alexander half of the Persian empire in exchange for peace.

00:12:24.002 --> 00:12:30.322
This was only two years into Alexander's campaign, and to think, he had already achieved an

00:12:30.322 --> 00:12:36.322
offer of receiving half of the richest and most powerful empire in the world at that time.

00:12:37.522 --> 00:12:42.112
His generals urged him to accept it, but Alexander would not listen.

00:12:42.702 --> 00:12:47.562
He rejected the offer, effectively declaring to the Persian king that he would

00:12:47.562 --> 00:12:52.622
stop at nothing; he would pursue him to take the entirety of his kingdom.

00:12:53.882 --> 00:12:56.982
It would take a couple of years, but after conquering

00:12:57.032 --> 00:13:00.612
Egypt, Alexander turned his attention back eastwards.

00:13:01.592 --> 00:13:07.482
On October 1st, 331 BC, his forces met those of the

00:13:07.482 --> 00:13:11.722
Persian Empire at Gaugamela, in modern-day northern Iraq.

00:13:13.512 --> 00:13:17.782
After the defeat a couple of years prior, Darius III had wasted

00:13:17.782 --> 00:13:21.952
no time in building up his army in preparation for the inevitable.

00:13:23.272 --> 00:13:29.932
His forces were formidable, war elephants, chariots with scythes, sharp

00:13:29.932 --> 00:13:35.352
knives, coming out of their wheels, an estimated 10,000 highly-skilled Greek

00:13:35.382 --> 00:13:41.532
mercenaries and a similar number of Persian “immortals”, elite foot soldiers.

00:13:42.832 --> 00:13:48.102
All in all, the Persian army is thought to have numbered around 100,000,

00:13:48.492 --> 00:13:52.172
although some ancient sources have put it as high as one million.

00:13:53.112 --> 00:13:57.642
Alexander’s forces, on the other hand, were a mere 47,000.

00:13:59.222 --> 00:14:03.352
They had been fighting almost non-stop for 5 years by this point.

00:14:03.932 --> 00:14:08.842
This would surely have made them tired, fatigued by five years of war.

00:14:09.532 --> 00:14:14.852
But it also made them incredibly well-drilled, effective, and acutely

00:14:14.852 --> 00:14:19.372
aware that if they were defeated, death or slavery awaited them.

00:14:20.492 --> 00:14:27.332
Against all the odds, they proved victorious, crushing the Persian army and forcing Darius to flee.

00:14:28.352 --> 00:14:33.802
This time he did not escape, and was killed by one of his own governors.

00:14:35.269 --> 00:14:40.362
Alexander was not best pleased that his rival had been murdered, because this was

00:14:40.362 --> 00:14:45.552
an unfair and dishonourable end for someone who was, at the end of the day, a great

00:14:45.552 --> 00:14:52.382
king, but this did mean that Alexander was now de facto ruler of the whole of Persia.

00:14:53.902 --> 00:14:57.842
He was only 25 years old at the time, and he had become

00:14:57.852 --> 00:15:01.192
without question the most powerful man in the world.

00:15:02.232 --> 00:15:06.482
Still, he continued eastwards, marching through large parts of modern

00:15:06.482 --> 00:15:12.242
day Iran, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Pakistan, and even ending up in India.

00:15:13.262 --> 00:15:17.592
And as all this was going on, he was still in charge of his kingdom

00:15:17.832 --> 00:15:21.502
back in Macedonia, as well as maintaining law and order in the

00:15:21.502 --> 00:15:25.402
regions that he had conquered, and were therefore under his control.

00:15:26.842 --> 00:15:32.802
To state the obvious, he was juggling a lot of balls; military conquests, governing

00:15:32.862 --> 00:15:37.922
acquired lands, keeping peace back at home, diplomacy with allies and enemies.

00:15:39.492 --> 00:15:44.302
By all accounts, and given that there was never a major rebellion against

00:15:44.302 --> 00:15:48.247
him during the thirteen years of the campaign, he was rather good at

00:15:48.247 --> 00:15:52.662
it, but this is not to say that everyone was happy with his leadership.

00:15:53.682 --> 00:15:59.222
As the years went by, and after he conquered Persia, he became increasingly Persian

00:15:59.392 --> 00:16:05.062
in his habits, and was criticised for abandoning the customs of his Greek homeland.

00:16:05.972 --> 00:16:11.232
He took three wives, which was unusual for Greeks, who were normally monogamous.

00:16:12.042 --> 00:16:17.352
And all three of his wives were not just not Greek; they were Persian.

00:16:18.752 --> 00:16:24.202
He also adopted the Persian custom of forcing his subjects to lie prostrate on

00:16:24.202 --> 00:16:29.992
the ground, bowing down before him, which was a decidedly un-Greek thing to do.

00:16:30.912 --> 00:16:37.542
Greece was a democracy at the time, without a monarch or emperor, so a Greek ruler forcing

00:16:37.542 --> 00:16:42.952
people to bow down before him was a sign to some that he had forgotten where he came from.

00:16:44.322 --> 00:16:48.452
Historians do write about people being unhappy with some of these

00:16:48.462 --> 00:16:52.732
tendencies, but not sufficiently to do anything drastic about it.

00:16:54.242 --> 00:16:59.712
There is one account of one of Alexander’s senior officers, a man called Cleitus the

00:16:59.712 --> 00:17:04.682
Black, who had been fighting by Alexander’s side right from the start and was close to him.

00:17:06.022 --> 00:17:13.052
Alexander and his officers were having a boozy celebration, and after many glasses of wine, Cleitus

00:17:13.122 --> 00:17:19.462
told Alexander that he thought he was becoming too Persian, and that he should remember his roots.

00:17:20.562 --> 00:17:25.932
Alexander didn’t say “you know what Cleitus, you’re probably right, thanks for the advice, old pal”.

00:17:26.992 --> 00:17:32.362
He picked up a spear and threw it at him, killing his old friend instantly.

00:17:33.502 --> 00:17:38.682
Eventually, in 326 BC, after reaching the Beas river in

00:17:38.682 --> 00:17:42.222
modern day Punjab, in India, Alexander did turn back.

00:17:43.302 --> 00:17:48.622
His kingdom had got too large, too wieldy, and he was aware that pushing

00:17:48.652 --> 00:17:52.692
any further east would take him further away from the centre of power,

00:17:53.082 --> 00:17:57.402
and potentially cause him problems with his increasingly homesick troops.

00:17:58.262 --> 00:18:01.942
His route back to Greece though was not direct, far from it.

00:18:02.562 --> 00:18:05.712
He took the opportunity to consolidate various parts of his

00:18:05.712 --> 00:18:09.912
territory, and was seemingly in no rush to return to Europe.

00:18:11.262 --> 00:18:17.992
He stopped off in Babylon, and then, in June of 323 BC, the unthinkable happened.

00:18:18.872 --> 00:18:21.872
He died, as you heard at the start of the episode.

00:18:23.442 --> 00:18:27.452
As to the cause of his death, there are multiple different views.

00:18:28.432 --> 00:18:33.082
Some say it was malaria, others it was typhoid or pneumonia.

00:18:33.852 --> 00:18:37.452
Others suggest that he was poisoned by an unhappy rival.

00:18:38.952 --> 00:18:43.242
